We have a set of ~10,000 circRNAs and we'd like to determine whether any of these circRNAs are translated and whether their protein products are presented on MHC class I molecules. Additionally, we're interested in seeing if circRNAs can be translated in the reverse (3'->5') direction. 

So for each circRNA, I predicted all possible open reading frames that span the back-splice junction (BSJ) in both the forward (canonical 5'->3') and backward (reversed 3'->5') directions. I then generated all 8–11mer peptide windows centered on the junction. 

If you have raw MS spectra, I've attached the full-length ORF protein FASTA files to re-search the raw spectra against an expanded database:
- forward_bsj_spanning_proteins.fasta
- backward_bsj_spanning_proteins.fasta 

There’s also the file: 
forward_rolling_circle_proteins.fasta
These are ORFs with no in-frame stop codon within the circRNA, meaning the ribosome could potentially traverse the circle multiple times (did not extract reverse for now as the number was super small). 

I've also attached a table of the pre-computed candidate 8–11mer peptides for direct string matching if you have a processed peptide list:
- all_candidate_bsj_peptides.tsv